    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Organic reach</strong> is the total number of unique users who see your social media content without paid promotion. Facebook organic reach has declined to approximately 5.2% of a page's followers as of 2024 (Hootsuite) — meaning a 10,000-follower page might reach only 520 people per post. Platform algorithms control organic reach based on engagement signals, content format, timing, and consistency.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Facebook avg reach</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~5.2% of followers</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Cost</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Zero</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">A local bakery switched from standard photo posts to Reels and saw its organic reach jump from 400 to 3,200 per post — an 8x increase with no ad spend, no new followers, and the same posting frequency. Organic reach responds to algorithm preferences, not just audience size.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is organic reach?</h2>
        <p>Organic reach is the count of unique individuals who saw a piece of social media content without the brand paying to distribute it. It is distinct from:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Paid reach</strong> — users who saw content because of a boosted post or ad campaign</li>
          <li><strong>Viral reach</strong> — users who saw content because someone in their network shared it (a subset of organic reach)</li>
          <li><strong>Impressions</strong> — total views, counting the same person multiple times</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Platforms like Facebook, Instagram, LinkedIn, and TikTok use algorithms to decide which posts to surface in each user's feed. Organic reach is what the algorithm decides to give you for free — based on how well your content performs with the initial test audience it exposes the post to.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">The algorithmic test model</div>
          <p>Every platform tests new posts with a small sample of followers (typically 3–10% of your audience). If that sample engages heavily within 30–60 minutes, the algorithm extends distribution to a broader audience. If not, the post stops spreading. This is why organic reach is not primarily about follower count — it is about engagement quality in the first hour.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why organic reach matters for social media strategy</h2>
        <p>Four reasons organic reach remains a key metric even as it declines:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Zero cost per impression.</strong> Organic reach distributes content with no media spend. A high-organic-reach account effectively gets paid advertising results without the budget. This compounds: 52 posts per year reaching 3,000 people each is 156,000 impressions at no direct cost.</li>
          <li><strong>Algorithm validation signal.</strong> High organic reach indicates the algorithm finds your content valuable. This creates a positive cycle: more reach means more engagement, which signals more reach on future posts. Accounts with consistent organic engagement get preferential treatment in distribution.</li>
          <li><strong>Audience quality.</strong> Organic viewers chose to follow you or matched algorithmically based on interest. This is a higher-intent audience than the cold paid audience of most ad campaigns. Organic reach converts at higher rates for many content objectives.</li>
          <li><strong>Foundation for paid amplification.</strong> Posts that perform well organically indicate content resonance. Boosting an organically strong post is more efficient than boosting one that hasn't proven itself — the algorithm already has performance data to work with.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How organic reach is calculated by platforms</h2>

        <h3>Engagement rate — the primary signal</h3>
        <p>Platforms track the ratio of engagements to viewers in the test window. Likes, comments, shares, and saves all contribute — but shares and saves carry more weight than likes on most platforms. A post with 100 views and 15 saves outperforms a post with 100 views and 15 likes in algorithmic distribution.</p>

        <h3>Content format preferences</h3>
        <p>Each platform actively promotes its preferred formats:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Instagram</strong> — Reels receive the highest organic reach amplification. Carousels receive strong distribution for dwell time. Static images receive the least.</li>
          <li><strong>LinkedIn</strong> — Native text posts with high dwell time (people read and pause) receive strong distribution. External links receive the least.</li>
          <li><strong>TikTok</strong> — Short-form video with strong watch-through rate (percentage of the video watched) receives the highest distribution.</li>
          <li><strong>Facebook</strong> — Video receives priority. Native documents and links receive less organic distribution than video or photo posts.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Timing and consistency</h3>
        <p>Publishing when your specific audience is active maximises the engagement quality in the first-hour test window. Consistent posting schedules train the algorithm to regularly offer your content to followers who engage repeatedly — building a predictable distribution base.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Organic reach benchmarks by platform</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
