        <h2 id="examples">Real organic reach examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Local bakery — 8x reach increase from format change</h3>
        <p>A local bakery was posting standard single-image photos and averaging 400 organic reaches per post with 2,800 followers. After switching to short Reels (15–30 seconds of food preparation footage), organic reach jumped to an average of 3,200 per post — an 8x increase with identical followers and posting frequency. No ad spend. No new followers. Only the format changed.</p>

        <h3>2. B2B consultant — 8,000 vs 45,000 impressions</h3>
        <p>A B2B marketing consultant averaged 8,000 impressions per Tuesday LinkedIn post. One post — a direct question to the marketing community about which channel was most overrated in 2026 — reached 45,000 impressions in 48 hours. The difference: the question format generated 147 comments in the first 4 hours, triggering algorithmic amplification beyond the follower base.</p>

        <h3>3. Ecommerce brand — format migration test</h3>
        <p>An ecommerce brand tracked organic reach by format over 60 days: static product photos averaged 1,200 reach, carousels averaged 2,800 reach, and Reels averaged 6,400 reach. Migrating 80% of their content calendar to Reels and carousels tripled average monthly organic reach with no increase in posting frequency.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Organic reach vs paid reach — when to use each</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Organic Reach</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Free — no media spend required</li>
              <li>Higher-intent audience (chose to follow or matched by interest)</li>
              <li>Builds long-term brand trust</li>
              <li>Compounds over time as engagement history grows</li>
              <li>Test content quality before spending budget</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Paid Reach</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Costs money per impression or click</li>
              <li>Cold audience (targeted by demographics or interest)</li>
              <li>Stops immediately when budget stops</li>
              <li>Scalable and controllable on demand</li>
              <li>Amplify content that already proved itself organically</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">8 practices to increase organic reach</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Post at peak audience activity times.</strong> The first 30–60 minutes after posting determine whether the algorithm amplifies or buries the post. Your audience needs to be active when you publish.</li>
          <li><strong>Use platform-preferred formats.</strong> Instagram rewards Reels, LinkedIn rewards text posts with high dwell time, TikTok rewards completion rate. Create in the format the platform promotes natively.</li>
          <li><strong>Prioritise saves and shares over likes.</strong> Ask "save this for later" rather than "double-tap to like." Saves are the strongest organic reach signal on Instagram; reshares are the strongest on LinkedIn and Twitter.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond to comments in the first hour.</strong> Your own replies add to the comment count and re-engage the algorithm's distribution test. A post with 20 comments gets significantly more reach than one with 5 likes and no comments.</li>
          <li><strong>Ask specific questions.</strong> Posts that end with a genuine question generate more comments than posts that don't. Comments are a strong algorithmic signal across all platforms.</li>
          <li><strong>Maintain consistent posting frequency.</strong> Irregular posting trains the algorithm to treat your account as an inconsistent publisher. Weekly consistency builds algorithmic preference over time.</li>
          <li><strong>Use native content — no external links in caption.</strong> Facebook and LinkedIn actively suppress posts with external links in the caption. If you need to link externally, move the link to the first comment.</li>
          <li><strong>Analyse which posts get the highest reach and replicate the pattern.</strong> Every account has content archetypes that perform above average. Identify the format, topic, and structure of those posts and build a content calendar around them.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — focusing on follower count over engagement quality</div>
          <p>An account with 50,000 followers and a 0.5% engagement rate has worse organic reach than an account with 5,000 followers and a 4% engagement rate. Platform algorithms are indifferent to follower counts — they amplify engagement signals. A large, disengaged audience actively harms organic reach by lowering the engagement rate in the algorithmic test window.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common organic reach mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Posting at the wrong time</strong> — publishing when your audience is asleep means the test window cohort is too small to generate algorithmic amplification.</li>
          <li><strong>External links in captions</strong> — Facebook and LinkedIn algorithmically deprioritise posts that send users off-platform. Move links to comments.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring format preferences</strong> — posting only static images on Instagram while the algorithm rewards Reels is leaving significant organic reach on the table.</li>
          <li><strong>Buying followers</strong> — fake followers never engage, which permanently lowers your engagement rate and signals low content quality to the algorithm.</li>
          <li><strong>Inconsistent posting</strong> — irregular publishing breaks the algorithmic distribution pattern your account has earned. A 2-week posting gap can reset reach performance.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating reach as the only metric</strong> — high reach with low engagement means your content isn't resonating. Optimise for engagement rate, not just raw reach numbers.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Why is organic reach declining?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>More content is competing for the same feed space — the number of posts on every platform has grown faster than the number of users. Platforms also benefit financially when brands pay for reach, so algorithms naturally favour paid distribution. However, organic reach remains viable for high-quality content that generates genuine early engagement.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do you increase organic reach?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Post at peak audience activity times, use platform-preferred formats (Reels on Instagram, text-native posts on LinkedIn), ask specific questions to generate comments, respond to comments in the first hour to boost the engagement signal, and maintain a consistent posting schedule. Quality of early engagement matters more than total follower count.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is a good organic reach rate?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Facebook: 5–10% of followers is solid; above 10% is strong. Instagram: 20–30% for accounts under 10,000 followers is standard; Reels regularly exceed 50% for engaged accounts. LinkedIn: smaller accounts can reach thousands beyond followers if content sparks conversation. Benchmarks vary by platform, industry, and account age.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between organic reach and impressions?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Organic reach counts unique users who saw your content — each person counted once regardless of how many times they saw it. Impressions count total views including multiple views by the same person. A post with 500 reach and 800 impressions means some users saw it more than once. Reach is the better measure for audience coverage; impressions for total exposure frequency.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Does organic reach affect paid ad performance?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Posts with strong organic engagement often perform better when boosted because the algorithm has already validated the content's appeal with your audience. Many effective social media strategies test content organically first, identify the top-performing posts, then boost those specifically — rather than boosting content that hasn't proven audience resonance.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

